T1  - When does international knowledge connectivity of global cities attract R&D investments? The role of concentrated ownership through organizational pipelines
AU  - Belderbos, René
AU  - Lee, Geon Ho
AU  - Mudambi, Ram
AU  - Du, Helen S.
AU  - Somers, Dieter
JO  - Research Policy
VL  - 53
IS  - 9
SP  - 105083
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/11/01/
SN  - 0048-7333
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.respol.2024.105083
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S004873332400132X
KW  - R&D
KW  - Knowledge connectivity
KW  - Global cities
KW  - Location decisions
AB  - We argue that the degree of concentrated ownership of international knowledge connections of a city in the hands of a small number of MNEs reduces the potential for knowledge spillovers and has a negative influence on the attractiveness of a city for new R&D investments. Ownership concentration in international knowledge connections reduces the positive influence of two complementary characteristics of international knowledge connectivity: the international connectedness (“depth”) and the geographical diversity (“breadth”) of the cities' international knowledge networks. Our analysis of the location decisions for 3235 new cross-border R&D investments made by 1599 firms distributed across 71 global cities (2003–2016) provides support for these hypotheses.
ER  - 
